I’m always asked what camera gear I use, I use the Nikon D850 with the Nikkor 70-200 f/2.8 lens and the Nikkor 200-500 f/5.6 lens. I’ve also been using my new monopod and tripod ALOT! When I’m going long distances, I carry the monopod with camera on it. Sometimes I don’t feel like taking it off, I just want the low shots so I end up adjusting the camera outward and straddling it on the ground, it’s pretty funny looking I’m sure 😂 I take the tripod for shorter distances because I haven’t mastered it yet. Sometimes when I adjust the legs, it almost knocks me over from the heaviness, but I’ll get better 😆 All photographers have their unique strategies and I’m having so much learning more and more. I have so many photography goals I’d love to reach this year! Happy Friday! And happy shooting!

Want to hear something super interesting about raccoons? Raccoon’s brains contain about 438 neurons to process information while dogs have about 530 neurons, however, raccoons can problem solve. And unlike dogs, raccoons have an extremely long memory, allowing them to recognize more objects, perceive changes in environment, and they exceed in problem solving tests, which is not only a step ahead of dogs but cats as well. Raccoons can find inventive ways to solve problems in ways humans aren’t unable to. Apes, monkeys, elephants and dolphins are among the most intelligent species on the planet, and raccoons are also up there on that list. In fact, they often score nearly as high as monkeys on intelligence tests. Being that monkeys score right below humans, raccoons are closer to human intelligence than one would expect. How can such a high intelligence animal even be considered a “pest”? They are so above and beyond a “pest”. The fact that humans even put that label on them shows such a lack of intelligence on our part.

Are you into “zoo” pictures? I took a few really pretty pictures at the Florida aquarium yesterday, there’s a section with animals, it was really beautiful. You want to see a few pics? We actually went because I googled Puffins in FL, and an article popped up about them being at the Florida Aquarium but I got so excited I didn’t read on about how their enclosure won’t be ready till 2024. So if I can hold out, it’ll be next year till I see my dream bird. But if I can’t, we’re going to head to Maine possibly beginning of next year. I rather see them in the wild anyway. When I was a kid, my family went to Maine and we did a whale watch and we passed by an island of rocks covered up in Puffins and seals. I can still see the vision in my head, I didn’t know what kind of birds they were until my Dad put the memory together for me and told me they were Puffins 😭 If only I was into photography at age 12 😂 They are so beautiful they don’t even look real. Definitely not mad about being able to wear a bathing suit in almost November. Grateful for that, grateful for the outdoors, and besides being grateful for family and friends, I’m so grateful for the ability to be so passionate for the things I love. A lot of people live without that fire in their soul. And for me, spotting wildlife feels like fireworks going off in my body every single time. Glad to be able to share my passion and my photography with you, it’s such a big part of who I am. Thanks so much for the DM’s that let me know I’ve changed their mind on an animal, or even noticed something that would have otherwise been passed by before unnoticed, or thinking of me when someone sees an animal. I love that. I’ve even had a picture sent to me of a stuffed animal raccoon when they were shopping with their kids lol. That kind of stuff makes me smile. Thanks for being here with me. I lose more followers than I gain, but I’m going to continue to share and hopefully make small impacts on people’s lives because it feels really good to be able to do that. Some of you have also made an impact on mine. And that’s what social media is about.
